1. results.csv
This is the most important data file in the repository. It contains the epoch-by-epoch training logs.

Contents: Columns for train/box_loss, train/cls_loss, metrics/precision, metrics/recall, and metrics/mAP50.

Purpose: It serves as the primary source for evaluating the model's accuracy and was used to generate the final performance audit.

2. detect.py
This is the inference script used to run the trained model on new, unseen images.

Contents: Python code that loads the YOLO weights (best.pt), processes an input image or video stream, and outputs bounding box coordinates with confidence scores.

Purpose: To demonstrate how the model would be used in a real-world clinical setting to identify jaundice markers on an infant's skin.

3. data.yaml
The configuration file for the dataset.

Contents: Paths to the train, val, and test image folders, along with the names of the classes (e.g., 0: jaundice, 1: normal).

Purpose: It tells the YOLOv11 framework how to read the data and how many categories it needs to learn.

4. Analysis_Report.pdf (or .docx)
The technical document exported from the Whiskers AI tool.

Contents: Structured tables and summaries identifying the best epoch (Epoch 49), accuracy trends, and an evaluation of the model's stability.

Purpose: To provide a human-readable summary of the machine learning results for stakeholders or medical professionals.

5. Folder Structure (/train, /valid, /test)
Contents: Thousands of annotated images used to teach the model what jaundice looks like.

Purpose: To ensure the model has enough variety in skin tones and lighting conditions to be accurate in a NICU environment.
